Further Developments

Current version: March 2026 – OpenFOAM v2406

The current implementation has some limitations and possible areas for improvement. The following points outline potential future developments:

1. Higher-order time discretization

At present, the solver supports only a first-order scheme for the temporal derivative.
Higher-order time discretization schemes could be implemented and systematically verified in order to improve accuracy.


2. Sensitivity to mesh non-orthogonality

The code becomes numerically unstable for highly non-orthogonal meshes.
In our tests, the largest value that still provided stable results corresponds to a maximum non-orthogonality of about 60.

Further work could investigate:

1) improved discretization strategies,

2) correction schemes for non-orthogonal meshes,

3) solver modifications to enhance robustness.


3. Source formulation

The acoustic source is currently implemented using a hard source approach.

At the IE-Fluids Laboratory, University of Trieste, we tested an alternative transparent source formulation in an in-house code. 
See the reference work: Lamonaca, F., Petris, G., Cianferra, M., & Armenio, V. (2024). Non-reflective hard source method for multiple physically extended sources and scattering bodies. Physics of Fluids, 36(3).
Validation tests indicate that this method performs better when the source is located close to reflecting boundaries.
However, this approach has not yet been implemented in the present OpenFOAM version.
